SIMPLE: polonaise
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Polonaise
<hw>Po`lo*naise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>polonais</ets>, <ets>polonaise</ets>, Polish.]</ety> <def>Of or
pertaining to the Poles, or to Poland.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>Polonese</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polonaise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Polonaise
<hw>Po`lo*naise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also
<ets>Polonese</ets> and <ets>Polonoise</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The Polish language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An article of dress for women, consisting of a body
and an outer skirt in one piece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A stately Polish dance tune, in
3-4 measure, beginning always on the beat with a quaver followed by a
crotchet, and closing on the beat after a strong accent on the second
beat; also, a dance adapted to such music; a polacca.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polonese</ent>⟦br⟧
